Revert P1 ‚Äî remove the registry-level PermissionEnforcer wiring

Patch 0003 (P1) attached a `PermissionEnforcer` to the tool registry as
defense-in-depth on top of the existing `ConversationRuntime` policy
gate. In practice this created two uncoordinated gates and made the
hardened config unusable.

Discovered 2026-04-24 during a probe with qwen2.5:7b under `default`
(= ReadOnly) active mode:

1. Model called `bash` with `ls -la`.
2. The high-level gate (`PermissionPolicy::authorize_with_context` in
   `ConversationRuntime::execute_turn`) correctly matched the
   `ask: [bash]` catch-all, prompted the user, and received approval.
3. The low-level enforcer (added by P1) then independently denied the
   call: `classify_bash_permission` returned `WorkspaceWrite`,
   `active_mode (ReadOnly) >= required (WorkspaceWrite)` is false,
   `EnforcementResult::Denied`. The user's approval at the higher
   gate was not visible to the lower gate.

Root issue: `PermissionEnforcer::check_with_required_mode` does pure
mode-ordering comparison and consults no allow/ask/deny rules.
`classify_bash_permission` never returns `ReadOnly` as the required
mode (only `WorkspaceWrite` for safe commands, `DangerFullAccess`
otherwise), so under `ReadOnly` active mode no bash invocation can
ever pass the second gate.

The right design ‚Äî if anyone wants per-command classification as
defense-in-depth ‚Äî is to plumb `classify_bash_permission` into the
high-level gate's `required_mode_for(...)` lookup so a single gate
evaluates everything. This patch only reverts the broken wiring; it
does not attempt that refactor.

Leaves the `PermissionEnforcer` re-export in `runtime/src/lib.rs`
(added by P1) intact, since it's harmless on its own and may be
useful for any future code that wants to use the enforcer correctly.
